long_desc.thetext:
The problems are indeed due to an attempt to make EMF work in a different way.

Specifically the problem is that EmfModelResourceFactory has a non-standard Resource cache with a heuristic to determine which cache entries can be safeRemove'd.

I don't understand the heuristic and it is clearly failing.

---

More generally:

EmfModel::createResourceSet() {
 ResourceSet resourceSet = new EmfModelResourceSet();
		resourceSet.getResourceFactoryRegistry().getExtensionToFactoryMap().put("*", EmfModelResourceFactory.getInstance());
		return resourceSet;
	}

This is very smelly; occluding the user's ResourceFactory registrations. The Resource and ResourceFactory are part of the used model design; it is dangerous to change them.

EmfModelResourceSet::createResource(URI uri)

			// Added code to copy the EPackages of the old resource set
			// into the new resource set
			if (result.getResourceSet() != null) {
				for (String s : result.getResourceSet().getPackageRegistry().keySet()) {
					this.getPackageRegistry().put(s, result.getResourceSet().getPackageRegistry().get(s));
				}
			}

I've no idea why this would be a good idea.

The override is certainly wrong since it subverts the redirection to content-types. I expect this may make the delicate UML content-type registrations fail.


EmfModelResourceFactory::configure()

Overriding the user default load options does not seem like a good idea. You can specify an alternate set of options to be merged when loading..


EmfModelResourceFactory::createResource(URI uri) {
...
if (resourceFactory != null && resourceFactory.getClass() != XMIResourceFactoryImpl.class) {
	resource = resourceFactory.createResource(uri);
}
else {
	resource = new EmfXMIResource(uri);
}

This is really odd. How can it be useful to change functionality for precisely XMIResourceFactoryImpl but not for derived XMIResourceFactory's? Why is it appropriate to change XMIResources created by file extension but not those created by content-type?

===

I strongly recommend eliminating all overrides of EMF functionality, it risks making Epsilon incompatible with the rest of the Eclipse modeling ecosystem.

If you want a smart Resource cache have a look at ResourceSetImpl's

  protected ResourceLocator resourceLocator;

It was added to improve Xtext efficiency.

The property access recorder is currently only used internally by EGL, but we could easily make this available to clients of the E?L languages. For example, the following should be possible:

recorder = module.getContext().getPropertyAccessRecorder();

module.parse("...")
recorder.startRecording();
module.execute();
recorder.stopRecording();

System.out.println(recorder.getPropertyAccesses());

As EGL uses an internal property access recorder to build its fine grained trace model, it makes sense to support multiple property access recorders:

recorder = new PropertyAccessRecorder();
recorder = module.getContext().getPropertyAccessRecorders().add(recorder);

module.parse("...")
recorder.startRecording();
module.execute();
recorder.stopRecording();

System.out.println(recorder.getPropertyAccesses());

Actually, a little bit of caching seems to be making this possible (see minimal example below)

PropertyRecorderWorkbench.java
---
public class PropertyRecorderWorkbench {

	public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {
		new PropertyRecorderWorkbench().run();
	}

	public void run() throws Exception {
		EolModule module = new EolModule();
		module.parse("p.name = 'foo'; p.asBag().collect(p|p.name).println();");
		module.getContext().getFrameStack().
			putGlobal(Variable.createReadOnlyVariable("p", new Person()));
		module.getContext().getExecutorFactory().addExecutionListener(new PropertyRecorder());
		module.execute();
	}

	class Person {

		protected String name;

		public void setName(String name) {
			this.name = name;
		}

		public String getName() {
			return name;
		}
	}

}

PropertyRecorder.java
---
public class PropertyRecorder implements IExecutionListener {

	WeakHashMap<AST, Object> cache = new WeakHashMap<AST, Object>();

	@Override
	public void finishedExecuting(AST ast, Object result, IEolContext context) {
		// Cache the result of the LHS of x.y expressions if a weak hash map
		if (ast.getParent().getType() == EolParser.POINT 
				&& ast.getParent().getFirstChild() == ast) {
			cache.put(ast, result);
		} // Detect property calls
		else if (ast.getType() == EolParser.POINT 
				&& ast.getParent().getType() != EolParser.ASSIGNMENT 
				&& ast.getSecondChild().getChildCount() == 0) {

			System.out.println("Accessed property " + 
					ast.getSecondChild().getText() + 
					" of " + 
					cache.get(ast.getFirstChild()));
		}
	}

	@Override
	public void aboutToExecute(AST ast, IEolContext context) {}

}


Can you spot any obvious problems with this approach?

Looks pretty good! I've made some changes to handle:

* Nested property accesses: person.enemy.name should capture both <"enemy" on "person"> and <"name" on "person.enemy">

* Property accesses that are on the _right-hand side_ of an assignment: var name = person.name should capture <"name" on "person">

* Point expressions that are not model-based property accesses: Person.all should capture nothing.

I'll keep working on this, as I suspect there may be some other cases we've overlooked.

--

public class PropertyAccessExecutionListener implements IExecutionListener {

	private final Collection<IPropertyAccessRecorder> recorders = new LinkedList<IPropertyAccessRecorder>();
	private final WeakHashMap<AST, Object> cache = new WeakHashMap<AST, Object>();

	public PropertyAccessExecutionListener(IPropertyAccessRecorder... recorders) {
		this.recorders.addAll(Arrays.asList(recorders));
	}

	@Override
	public void aboutToExecute(AST ast, IEolContext context) {}

	@Override
	public void finishedExecuting(AST ast, Object result, IEolContext context) {
		// When the left-hand side of a point expression has been executed, store the object on 
		// which the point expression was invoked, so that we can pass it to any property access recorders
		if (isLeftHandSideOfPointExpression(ast)) {
			cache.put(ast, result);
		}

		// When a property access is executed, notify the recorders
		if (isPropertyAccessExpression(ast)) {

			final Object modelElement = cache.get(ast.getFirstChild());
			final String propertyName = ast.getSecondChild().getText();

			if (isModelBasedProperty(modelElement, propertyName, context)) {
				for (IPropertyAccessRecorder recorder : this.recorders) {
					recorder.record(modelElement, propertyName);
				}
			}
		}
	}

	private boolean isLeftHandSideOfPointExpression(AST ast) {
		return ast.getParent().getType() == EolParser.POINT && 
		       ast.getParent().getFirstChild() == ast;
	}

	private boolean isPropertyAccessExpression(AST ast) {
		return ast.getType() == EolParser.POINT &&          // AST is a point expression  
		       ast.getSecondChild().getChildCount() == 0 && // AST's right-hand side is not a method call
		       !isAssignee(ast);                            // AST is not the left-hand side of an assignment
	}

	// Determines whether a property access is model-based (and not, for example, for an extended property) 
	private boolean isModelBasedProperty(Object object, String property, IEolContext context) {
		return context.getIntrospectionManager().isModelBasedProperty(object, property, context);
	}

	// Determines whether the specified AST is the left-hand side of an assignment expression
	private boolean isAssignee(AST ast) {
		return ast.getParent().getType() == EolParser.ASSIGNMENT &&
			   ast.getParent().getFirstChild() == ast;
	}
}

Petri Savola from the forums has issues with the FixGMFGen.eol script bundled in Eugenia. Apparently, he has manually added labels to some of the EReferences in his classes and FixGMFGen.eol is producing an error when it tries to check if they should be labelled or not:

http://www.eclipse.org/forums/index.php/t/629163/

Since Eugenia does not handle EReferences as labels but as affixed nodes or links, I think it should be safe to simply return false in a new variant of isLabelled() for EReferences:

@cached
operation ECore!EReference isLabelled() : Boolean {
	return false;
}

Another option might be to implement the call stack monitoring behaviour as a new IExecutionListener which we could attach to the ExecutorFactory. This would also enable us to track the call stack at a more fine-grained level. For example under the current implementation, in the following sample program

1.foo();

operation Integer foo() {
	self.bar();
}

operation Integer bar() {
	return a;
}

the generated trace does not go all the way up to 1.foo(). Any thoughts?

That's a good point. Since exceptions are context-less, I suspect that after printing the reason of an exception, client code would have to call something like this: 

module.getContext().getExecutorFactory().getCallStackManager().printCallStack(module.getContext().getErrorStream());

which is not too bad I guess.
